00:00:05.870 --> 00:00:08.796
number in nerd culture.

00:00:08.796 --> 00:00:09.242
PHIL MORIARTY: Good.

00:00:09.242 --> 00:00:09.900
Good, good, good.

00:00:09.900 --> 00:00:11.760
Did you want to do something
with 42?

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:12.490
JAMES GRIME: Yes.

00:00:12.490 --> 00:00:13.540
So you take a piece of paper.

00:00:13.540 --> 00:00:14.420
It's very thin.

00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:16.030
Let's fold this in half.

00:00:16.030 --> 00:00:17.020
Fold it in half again.

00:00:17.020 --> 00:00:18.210
Fold it in half again.

00:00:18.210 --> 00:00:22.090
Imagine you can keep doing this,
and in reality you can't

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:22.690
keep doing this.

00:00:22.690 --> 00:00:24.660
But imagine you can keep folding
it in half, and each

00:00:24.660 --> 00:00:27.700
time you do, it will double
in thickness.

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:32.259
And if you fold it 42 times,
that's enough to reach from

00:00:32.259 --> 00:00:34.220
the Earth to the moon.

00:00:39.710 --> 00:00:43.810
You notice when 42 turns up,
you keep noticing it.

00:00:43.810 --> 00:00:47.360
But that's not really all that
remarkable, since any two

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:52.210
digit number will turn up one
hundredth of the time.

