00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:13.210
GERARDO ADESSO: This
number, 42, is said

00:03:13.210 --> 00:03:15.270
to be a pronic number.

00:03:15.270 --> 00:03:16.172
JAMES GRIME: A what, sorry?

00:03:16.172 --> 00:03:17.375
GERARDO ADESSO: A
pronic number.

00:03:17.375 --> 00:03:18.300
JAMES GRIME: What
does that mean?

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:20.230
GERARDO ADESSO: I can
write it for you.

00:03:20.230 --> 00:03:24.860
So a pronic number is a number
which is obtained as the

00:03:24.860 --> 00:03:28.360
multiplication of two
successive integers.

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:31.230
So for instance, in the
case of 42, 42 is

00:03:31.230 --> 00:03:33.020
equal to 6 times 7.

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:36.320
These are one after the other,
and any number which is like

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:37.180
this is called pronic.

00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:40.770
For instance, 2 times 3,
3 times 4, and so on.

00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:43.830
JAMES GRIME: Douglas Adams,
I think chose this number

00:03:43.830 --> 00:03:46.370
because it kind of has
a funny sound.

00:03:46.370 --> 00:03:51.110
40, all those O's, 42,
it's a funny sound.

00:03:51.110 --> 00:03:54.020
PHIL MORIARTY: Again, if you go
on the web, and if you read

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:57.010
some of the articles about 42,
there are arguments ranging

00:03:57.010 --> 00:04:01.330
from, well actually it's 101010
in binary, which is a

00:04:01.330 --> 00:04:02.290
nice binary number.

00:04:02.290 --> 00:04:04.840
And in fact, in the television
